\begin{slide}
\slname{Background}
\itms{
  \item Before DNS, there was a global {\tt hosts.txt}
  \item DNS is an attempt to distributed {\tt hosts.txt}, but:
	\itms{
	\item Everyone has to be a DNS admin.
	\item Configuring DNS properly is tedious and time-consuming.
	\item I can't have a domain without finding someone to serve my names.
	}
  \item A peer-to-peer framework is better.
}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}
\slname{IP-based DNS Authentication}
\itms{
  \item Assume that IP transport layer can be trusted.
  \item Clients start by trusting some IP addresses for some parts of the hierarchy.
  \ittms{ \item Ex.: Trust well-known root server addresses for {\tt *} }
  \item Trusted servers delegate authority to other IP addresses.
  \ittms { \item Ex.: Trust 18.18.2.25 for {\tt *.mit.edu} }
  \item Works well for research system.
  \item Not a great assumption if names are vital.
}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}
\slname{DNSSEC: Public key-based DNS Authentication}
\itms{
  \item Assume that public key cryptography can be trusted.
  \item Clients start by trusting some public keys for some parts of the hierarchy.
  \ittms{ \item Ex.: Trust well-known root server keys for {\tt *} }
  \item Trusted servers delegate authority to other public keys.
  \ittms { \item Ex.: Trust $\mathit{Pub}_{\mathrm{MIT}}$ for {\tt *.mit.edu} }
  \item (Hopefully) much more secure.
}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}
\slname{Side Effects of Authentication}
\itms{
  \item IP authentication dictated lookup algorithm.
  \item DNSSEC separates lookup from verification:
  \ittms{ \item It doesn't matter where we get the data; we can check it.}
  \item Can now explore other storage and service models.
}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}
\slname{We explored DNS over Chord}
\itms{
  \item SHA1(name, query-type) is storage key for DHash
  \item Lookup retrieves records and verifies them (DNSSEC).
}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}
